node.text:
The best leg ever 🐶🦵You can check how to get your photos promoted in our account, use the link in our bio @tripfever

Tag someone who has to see this! This is the story of Andrea Pusateri, a paralympic athlete and his adorable dog Sally:

"At the age of three and a half, I escaped from my mother’s hands while a train was passing at the Monza’s train station. She laid down her life to save me and I lost both of my legs, but the doctors were able to reimplant my left leg with an operation. When I was a child, I practiced several sports until I run into the bicycle. In 2008, I began my agonistic carrier in the Paralympic world, where I achieved several results at a national and international level."

How awe-inspiring is Andrea's story? 🐶

📽 @pusateriandrea
📍Cancano Lake, Italy
🎶 Tommee Profitt - In The End (Mellen Gi Remix) [feat. Fleurie]

node.text:
Copenhagen 😍 You can check how to get your photos promoted in our account, use the link in our bio @tripfever

Capital of Denmark is a unique city, characterized by its canals, cycling culture, strong economy, and happy locals. It is also UNESCO's World Capital of Architecture 2023. In 2 years, the capital will host events exploring how architecture can contribute to achieving a more sustainable future.

📸 @copenhagenbycosedis 
📍Copenhagen, Denmark

Being a real life astronaut, performing a space walk.

The International Space Station (ISS) is a modular space station (habitable artificial satellite) in low Earth orbit. It is a multinational collaborative project involving five participating space agencies: NASA (United States), Roscosmos (Russia), JAXA (Japan), ESA (Europe), and CSA (Canada). The ownership and use of the space station is established by intergovernmental treaties and agreements.

node.text:
Moray eels 🖐 We can promote your photos in our account. Check the link in our bio for instructions: @tripfever

Tag a @nature lover! 😍

Fun fact: 
A moray eel appears dangerous because it continually exposes its mouth and teeth. This action, however, is not a hostile gesture, but simply the way an eel breathes. Morays have large mouths and powerful jaws with a vice-like grip. Most species have sharp, thin teeth that protrude from the upper and lower jaws, and sometimes from the roof of the mouth. The teeth point backwards to prevent slippery prey from escaping. 

Because most moray eels have low dorsal (top) fins and lack pectoral and pelvic fins, they do not have a great amount of lateral stability. It is not uncommon to see moray eels lying or drifting on their sides or even upside down.

📸 @espekanela
📍Tenerife, Canary Islands, Spain
